mlvpn (0.4.0-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * mlvpn-tui: replace the single link table with a tabbed Links /
    Daemon / Logs view. Links gains state-duration and cumulative
    tx/rx-byte columns; Daemon shows session id/uptime/rekey count,
    outbound queue depth and lifetime drops, the TUN interface's own
    kernel byte/error/drop counters, and machine-wide load/memory/
    uptime; Logs streams the daemon's own INFO+ log output live
    (Up/Down/PageUp/PageDown to scroll, auto-follows the tail unless
    scrolled back). Switch tabs with Tab/Shift+Tab or 1/2/3.
  * mlvpnd: the control-socket wire format (ipc::Snapshot) gained the
    fields the above needs -- a new daemon: DaemonSnapshot and
    new_log_lines: Vec<LogEntry>, both required (not optional), plus
    new per-link fields on LinkSnapshot. This is a breaking wire
    change: mlvpnd and mlvpn-tui must be upgraded together on a given
    host, since an old mlvpn-tui talking to a new mlvpnd (or vice
    versa) will fail to parse the control socket's JSON.
  * New in-memory log ring (logbuf.rs) feeding mlvpn-tui's Logs tab,
    filtered to INFO+ independent of the daemon's own configured log
    level so a debug/trace run can't flood it. Session/rekey metadata
    moved off the per-packet session lock into its own SessionMeta to
    avoid adding contention to that hot path.

 -- Jeff Parrish PC Services <www.jpps.us>  Sat, 18 Jul 2026 00:00:00 -0500

mlvpn (0.3.7-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Fix compute_achieved_mbps's elapsed-time floor silently capping
    active-bandwidth-probe results at ~229 Mbps on fast links. The
    1ms floor was high enough to override real, correctly-measured
    durations for bursts that legitimately completed faster than
    that, so achieved_mbps ceilinged at the same value every time --
    confirmed from production logs showing the exact same figure
    recurring on a fast link. Since active_bandwidth_mbps feeds the
    scheduler's throughput weighting, this systematically
    underweighted a link relative to its real capacity. Lowered the
    floor to 1 microsecond (Instant has nanosecond resolution, so
    this still only guards the literal zero/negative case).

 -- Jeff Parrish PC Services <www.jpps.us>  Sat, 18 Jul 2026 00:00:00 -0500

mlvpn (0.3.6-1) unstable; urgency=high

  * Fix postinst corruption: dh_installdeb substitutes every occurrence
    of the literal marker token in a maintainer script, not just the
    one intended insertion point -- this script's own explanatory
    comments repeated that token five more times in prose, so each got
    a second copy of debhelper's generated systemctl restart/
    daemon-reload code spliced into the middle of the sentence,
    breaking the script's syntax and failing dpkg --configure with
    exit 127 on a real install (mlvpn 0.3.5 never actually installed
    successfully as a result). Rewrote every comment to describe the
    marker without repeating the literal token pattern debhelper
    matches on.

 -- Jeff Parrish PC Services <www.jpps.us>  Fri, 17 Jul 2026 00:00:00 -0500

mlvpn (0.3.5-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * A link's remote_addr now accepts a DNS hostname, not just a literal
    IP (e.g. "bgp.example.com:51000"). Resolved once at startup with a
    10s timeout; a hostname resolving to both an A and AAAA record
    prefers IPv6 unless local_addr pins the family.
  * New outbound queue overflow logging, modeled on the original C
    MLVPN's freebuffer_t: tun_reader and the actual per-link send are
    now split across a bounded channel, so a send side that falls
    behind drops packets and logs a WARN-level "outbound queue
    overflowed" line (with a drop count) instead of silently losing
    them in the kernel's TUN queue, as happened below. Silent on a
    healthy tunnel.
  * Performance: bonded throughput still plateaued well below what the
    links could do individually, even after 0.3.2's cross-link lock fix.
    A real two-host test pushing 200 Mbps of small UDP datagrams
    (~19,000 packets/sec) found a hard, flat ~65% loss ceiling. Root
    cause: send_scheduled cloned every configured link's full Link
    (including every LinkConfig String field) on every single outgoing
    packet just to let the scheduler pick one and discard the rest --
    the heap allocation and per-link lock/clone overhead of that
    outpaced packet arrival at high rates, silently overflowing the
    kernel's TUN queue before mlvpnd ever read the dropped packets.
    Scheduler::select now works off a Copy-only LinkScore snapshot and
    returns just the winning link's index, so only that one link is
    ever locked-and-cloned. See docs/performance-tuning.md.

 -- Jeff Parrish PC Services <www.jpps.us>  Fri, 17 Jul 2026 00:00:00 -0500

mlvpn (0.3.4-1) unstable; urgency=high

  * Fix the 0.3.3 restart-on-upgrade fix always losing the race: it
    checked/restarted the service before #DEBHELPER#, but debhelper's
    own generated postinst code (compat 10+ default
    --restart-after-upgrade, with --no-start only suppressing the
    "start" half) unconditionally stops mlvpnd *after* that on every
    upgrade -- so 0.3.3's restart always got immediately undone,
    leaving the service down after every upgrade exactly as before.
    Fixed by recording whether the service was active before anything
    in this postinst (debhelper's own code included) can touch it, and
    restarting -- last, after #DEBHELPER# -- based on that recorded
    state instead. Found on a real two-host upgrade immediately after
    0.3.3 shipped.

 -- Jeff Parrish PC Services <www.jpps.us>  Fri, 17 Jul 2026 00:00:00 -0500

mlvpn (0.3.3-1) unstable; urgency=high

  * Fix restarting either side of a tunnel silently stopping the other
    side too, which then required a manual restart there. A
    peer-initiated Disconnect makes mlvpnd exit cleanly (code 0) by
    design, and the previous Restart=on-failure systemd policy never
    restarts a process that exited 0 -- so restarting one side for any
    reason (a routine package upgrade, a manual systemctl restart) sent
    the other side a graceful Disconnect and left it stopped
    indefinitely. This made 0.3.2's own restart-on-upgrade fix worse in
    practice: upgrading one host now reliably stopped its peer.
    systemd/mlvpn.service now uses Restart=always, so any exit -- this
    one included -- gets the daemon back up within RestartSec=2; an
    explicit systemctl stop is unaffected, since systemd always honors
    a deliberate stop regardless of Restart=.
  * Fix mlvpn-tui failing with "multiple control sockets found" once
    [command] enabled = true was set. Auto-detection matched any file
    under /run/mlvpn ending in .sock, which also matched the
    <tunnel>.command.sock write-capable command socket -- a completely
    different protocol, not the streaming snapshot mlvpn-tui actually
    reads. Now explicitly excludes *.command.sock.

 -- Jeff Parrish PC Services <www.jpps.us>  Fri, 17 Jul 2026 00:00:00 -0500

mlvpn (0.3.2-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Performance: bonding two links together could be *slower* than using
    either one alone. All links shared one single lock over every
    link's metadata (stats, state, learned remote address), so two
    links' receive tasks serialized against each other on every packet
    even though they touch completely disjoint data. Each link now has
    its own independent lock, removing that cross-link contention
    entirely. See docs/performance-tuning.md.
  * Add: mlvpn-tui's header now shows this machine's own hostname
    alongside the tunnel name and mode, so a snapshot copied out of
    context is unambiguous about which end of the tunnel it came from.
  * Fix: systemd/mlvpn.service's PrivateDevices=no had a trailing inline
    comment on the same line, which systemd's unit-file parser doesn't
    support. Moved the comment to its own line above.
  * Fix: the mlvpn system user's primary group could end up as nogroup
    instead of mlvpn on an existing install. Both the .deb postinst and
    the .rpm %pre scriptlet now enforce this on every install/upgrade.
  * Fix: the .deb package now restarts mlvpnd after an upgrade if it was
    already running, instead of leaving the old binary running in
    memory until the operator remembered to restart it by hand. (The
    .rpm package already did this via %systemd_postun_with_restart.)

 -- Jeff Parrish PC Services <www.jpps.us>  Fri, 17 Jul 2026 00:00:00 -0500

mlvpn (0.3.1-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Fix the initial handshake exiting the whole daemon if every
    configured link's peer is unreachable at startup. Under systemd's
    default Restart=on-failure, a peer that stayed unreachable for a
    few minutes could trip StartLimitBurst and leave the unit
    permanently failed. mlvpnd now logs a warning and retries with
    exponential backoff in the background indefinitely instead,
    matching WireGuard/the original MLVPN. Found on a real two-host
    deployment.
  * Performance: request an 8 MiB kernel socket buffer per link
    (SO_RCVBUFFORCE/SO_SNDBUFFORCE, falling back to plain SO_RCVBUF/
    SO_SNDBUF), instead of relying on the stock ~208KB Linux default,
    which silently drops packets once a fast link's bandwidth-delay
    product exceeds it. See docs/performance-tuning.md.
  * Fix a stale handshake reply being able to permanently starve every
    future retry once the initial handshake started retrying
    indefinitely (previous bullet): race_handshake_reply now also
    requires a reply's session id to match the current attempt's,
    instead of only checking source address and packet type. Caught by
    this project's own integration tests immediately after the retry
    change above.

 -- Jeff Parrish PC Services <www.jpps.us>  Thu, 16 Jul 2026 00:00:00 -0500

mlvpn (0.3.0-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Add self-healing link reconnection: a link whose interface is fully
    removed and recreated (e.g. a USB LTE modem replugged) now gets its
    socket automatically rebound instead of staying dead until the
    daemon restarts.
  * Add handshake racing across every configured link: the client tries
    the initial handshake on all configured links at once instead of
    only the first one, so a single down link at startup no longer
    blocks the tunnel from coming up.
  * Add rekeying and session migration: sessions are now periodically
    rekeyed (crypto.rekey_interval_secs, default 120s) with a brief
    overlap window so in-flight packets aren't dropped during the swap.
  * Add graceful shutdown: mlvpnd now handles SIGINT/SIGTERM
    (systemctl stop sends SIGTERM, which wasn't previously handled at
    all) by notifying its peer and exiting cleanly.
  * Add per-link bandwidth cap enforcement (a real, enforced ceiling
    rather than just a scoring bias) and an opt-in
    scheduler.redundant_mode that sends every packet on every
    currently-up link at once, trading bandwidth for reliability on
    small, latency-critical tunnels.
  * Add a runtime link-control command socket ([command] enabled, off
    by default): mlvpnd set-link <link> <enable|disable> pins a link
    out of scheduling without editing the config and restarting.
  * Add IPv6 support to the bonded links themselves: each [[links]]
    entry is now independently IPv4 or IPv6, inferred from
    remote_addr/local_addr, so a tunnel can mix address families
    across its links. Existing IPv4-only configs are unaffected.
  * Add periodic tunnel auto-tuning, all opt-in and off by default:
    reorder_window_ms, probe_interval_ms, and EWMA alpha can each
    re-tune themselves from live link conditions instead of staying
    fixed at their configured value for the tunnel's whole life.
  * Add active bandwidth probing (scheduler.active_bandwidth_probing,
    opt-in): periodically measures a link's real achieved throughput
    with a small, rate-limited packet burst instead of only ever
    inferring it from real traffic that happens to be flowing.
  * New integration test harness (tests/veth_*.rs) exercising all of
    the above against two real mlvpnd processes in Linux network
    namespaces connected by real veth pairs.
  * Fix log output carrying embedded ANSI color escape codes even when
    not writing to an interactive terminal (e.g. journald, a log
    file): tracing_subscriber's color coding defaulted to on
    unconditionally; now explicitly disabled.
  * Fix a race in the initial handshake's retry loop: a late reply
    arriving just after one attempt's timeout but during a later
    attempt's window would fail to decrypt (wrong ephemeral) and then
    poison every remaining retry via the existing stale-duplicate
    protection, dooming the whole handshake even though the peer had a
    valid session waiting. Each initial-handshake attempt now uses its
    own session id; rekeying is unaffected.

 -- Jeff Parrish PC Services <www.jpps.us>  Wed, 15 Jul 2026 00:00:00 -0500

mlvpn (0.2.0-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Add IPv6 support to the mlvpn0 TUN interface: tunnel.address6 (an
    optional IPv6 CIDR) assigns a second address family to the same
    device alongside the existing IPv4 tunnel.address, sharing the same
    encrypted session and bonded links. The underlying UDP transport
    between mlvpnd instances is still IPv4-only (see ARCHITECTURE.md
    §11 item 4); this is dual-stack payload, not dual-stack transport.
  * Add adaptive tunnel MTU: each bonded link's real physical interface
    MTU is queried via SIOCGIFMTU at bind time (link.rs), and
    tunnel.mtu is now treated as an upper bound rather than a fixed
    value -- main.rs's effective_tunnel_mtu() auto-clamps it down (with
    a logged warning) if it would fragment against the smallest
    detected physical MTU, turning the previous startup-only advisory
    warning into a real, self-correcting default.
  * Add TCP MSS clamping (mss.rs), on by default via the new
    tunnel.clamp_mss config option: rewrites the MSS option of TCP
    SYN/SYN-ACK segments (IPv4 and IPv6) transiting the tunnel to fit
    the effective tunnel MTU, avoiding the "PMTUD black hole" failure
    mode where a network silently drops the ICMP messages TCP would
    otherwise use to discover the right segment size on its own.
  * Add ARCHITECTURE.md's "Relationship to the original MLVPN" section:
    credits zehome/MLVPN (Laurent Coustet) for the bonding/monitoring/
    failover concept this project is a from-scratch Rust rewrite of,
    and documents the specific reasons for the rewrite (binds to a
    network interface rather than an IP address so it survives DHCP/
    roaming changes, memory-safe implementation, Noise_IK handshake
    with forward secrecy instead of a shared password, and more).

 -- Jeff Parrish PC Services <www.jpps.us>  Mon, 13 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000

mlvpn (0.1.2-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * security: bump ratatui 0.29 -> 0.30, pulling in a patched lru
    (>= 0.16.3) that fixes a soundness issue in lru's IterMut affecting
    versions >= 0.9.0, < 0.16.3 (RUSTSEC advisory). ratatui 0.29 pins
    lru = "0.12.0", which cargo resolved to the vulnerable 0.12.5; a
    Cargo [patch] can't bridge that semver-incompatible pre-1.0 gap, so
    following ratatui's own dependency bump was the only real fix.
    lru is only ever reachable via mlvpn-tui (the monitoring binary);
    mlvpnd's core/data-path code doesn't depend on it. Reviewed
    ratatui's 0.30 breaking changes against src/bin/mlvpn-tui.rs's
    actual usage (no block::Title, Style/Stylize, Alignment, Marker, or
    generic Backend exposure) -- no source changes needed there, but
    default-features trimmed in Cargo.toml to avoid pulling in an
    unused `time` dependency from 0.30's new all-widgets default.
  * Raise minimum supported Rust toolchain to 1.86 (from 1.75), which
    ratatui 0.30 itself requires.
  * Audited every crate in Cargo.lock with a published RustSec
    advisory against our actual locked version (tokio, bytes, rand,
    tracing-subscriber, ring, time, snow, curve25519-dalek, aes-gcm,
    nix, zerocopy, hashbrown); all already resolve to patched versions
    under the existing Cargo.toml semver ranges, no further pins
    needed beyond the lru fix above.
  * Fix release.yml's RPM build (rockylinux9 leg): rpmbuild's internal
    BuildRequires check can't see the rustup-installed toolchain and
    failed with "cargo/rust >= 1.75 is needed" regardless of version;
    added rpmbuild -ba --nodeps, same reasoning as the .deb build's
    dpkg-buildpackage -d.
  * Fix RPM packaging failing with "Empty %files file
    debugsourcefiles.list": Cargo.toml's strip = true leaves no debug
    symbols for rpmbuild's find-debuginfo to extract. Added
    %global debug_package %{nil} to packaging/rpm/mlvpn.spec.

